	<h2>The Outlier in the Data</h2>
	<p>
		Harvard’s 75-year study on adult development reached a singular conclusion: 
		<strong>"Good relationships keep us happier and healthier."</strong> For a long time, I was the outlier in that data. I lost my father and several loved ones to the silent, suffocating trap of loneliness. Their departures left me in a void where I couldn't find the variables to solve my own life.
	</p>

	<h2>The Physics of Distance & The Math of Mind</h2>
	<p>
		To survive, I chose <strong>independence</strong>. I moved to Jeju Island, putting physical distance between my traumatic past and my fragile present. In the serene silence of Jeju, I discovered two transformative tools: <strong>Nature and Data.</strong>
	</p>
    
	<p>
		As a Math major, I started using the <strong>MUSE S</strong> headband to translate my invisible mental chaos into visible EEG data. For the first time, mindfulness wasn't just a "feeling"—it was a measurable optimization process.
	</p>

	<h2>From Self-Optimization to Relationship Healing</h2>
	<p>
		As I mastered my internal narrative through data-driven meditation, the resentment that had poisoned my life began to melt. I healed the relationship with my mother and reconnected with the world. 
	</p>
    <p>
        I realized a profound truth: <strong>To liberate others, you must first liberate yourself.</strong> My freedom became the blueprint for helping others escape their own prisons of isolation.
    </p>

